ce:section.ce:para:
This section describes the different synthesis strategies used to combine CDs and dendrimers to produce nanohybrids. These approaches (Fig. 2
                     ) were organized into four categories: covalent, non-covalent, casting, and sandwich methods. Moreover, diverse dendrimer types were used for nanohybrid formation, such as peptides, PAMAM, silicone and triazine dendrimers (Fig. 3
                     ).

CDs and dendrimers were also combined through non-covalent interactions, mainly relying on opposite surface charge attraction to form non-covalent nanohybrids (Table 2
                        ). The non-covalent method offers a more straightforward experimental strategy and setup because it requires only the presence of the two components to form a nanohybrid. Also, it allows the use of higher generations of dendrimers since the non-covalent interactions better preserve the PL properties of CDs and enable the formation of nanohybrids with higher loading capacities. Cationic-type dendrimers were used to interact with CDs presenting an anionic surface. For instance, graphene quantum dots were non-covalently combined with G5 PAMAM-NH2 dendrimers. Initially, the G5 PAMAM dendrimer was previously functionalized with the univalent radical of guanosine, the guanidyl (Gu+), forming G5 PAMAM-Gu+, and afterward mixed with GQDs, self-assembling by electrostatic interactions [58]. Using the same generation of PAMAM dendrimer, a different team prepared nanohybrids with CQDs that were previously synthesized using chitosan and PEG-4000 (polyethylene glycol) via the hydrothermal method. The G5 PAMAM dendrimer was first acetylated with acetic anhydride to convert 70% of primary amines into acetamide groups, accompanied by encapsulation of the anticancer anthracycline drug epirubicin (EPI). Then, the hydroxyl-terminated CQDs interacted with cationic EPI⊂G5-Ac85 dendrimer complexes to obtain CQDs@EPI⊂G5-Ac85 fluorescent nanohybrids [59]. Another study reported the conjugation between CQDs and G4 PAMAM dendrimers at room temperature by taking advantage of their surface charges, thus increasing the sensitivity of carbon quantum dots to detect explosive compounds [60]. Nanohybrids between CDs/DOX complexes and G5 PAMAM-RGD-TPGS dendrimers were prepared by non-covalent interaction for cancer theranostics (the RGD, cyclic arginine-glycine-aspartic peptide is a targeting ligand, and the d-α-tocopheryl polyethylene glycol 1000 succinate (TPGS) is a drug efflux inhibitor). First, the CDs were synthesized by the hydrothermal method using sodium citrate and ammonium bicarbonate. Afterward, CDs/DOX complexes were prepared by hydrogen bonding interaction and attached electrostatically at room temperature for 24 h to the previously functionalized G5 PAMAM-RGD-TPGS [61]. The same group also reported the preparation of G5-TPGS@y-CDs-DOX complexes by non-covalent interaction for chemotherapy purposes (Fig. 5
                        ). Yellow-fluorescent CDs were primarily synthesized using acetylsalicylic acid and the hydrothermal approach. Afterward, they are physically conjugated via electrostatic interaction with G5 PAMAM-TPGS forming the desired y-CD/dendrimer nanohybrid to deliver TPGS and DOX successfully to multi-drug resistant tumors [62]. In another work, our group [63], prepared CDs/dendrimer nanohybrids by non-covalent interaction between anionic-type CDs and cationic PAMAM dendrimers for bioimaging and gene delivery. Anionic surface CDs were hydrothermally synthesized using ascorbic acid as a precursor resulting in round-shaped CDs with an average size of 4 nm. Then, G4-G6 PAMAM-NH2 dendrimers were electrostatically attached at room temperature to anionic CDs forming G4-G6 CDs@PAMAM nanohybrids. The results showed that high-generation PAMAM dendrimers (G4-G6) could interact non-covalently with CDs. Interestingly, a clear pattern regarding the dendrimer generation vs. synthesis method is observed once non-covalent nanohybrids were prepared using high generation dendrimers while low generation ones were used in covalent nanohybrids. This trend is most likely related to the impact on the CDs fluorescence, but this subject will be further discussed in the optical properties section. Another reason may be related to the globular shape (which increases with the increase in generation) vs. the open-arm form (which decreases with the increase in generation) acquired by the dendrimer and the existence of generation-dependent cationic densities. Some drawbacks assigned to the non-covalent method are related to the random shape and large size and size dispersity acquired by this type of nanohybrids.

CDs and dendrimers were also combined by adapting biorecognition methodologies to the casting and sandwiching preparation methods (Table 3
                        ). The casting method is a simple and effective process for obtaining a nanofilm of CDs and dendrimers. This involves mixing the material with the right solvent and depositing the CDs and dendrimers onto a solid substrate. For instance, Lin et al. [64] mixed low-generation PAMAM dendrimers (G2) with GQDs. Primarily, GQDs were obtained from the laser-ablation method, and then a thin film of PAMAM dendrimers was fabricated by spin-coating on a Si-substrate. After, the as prepared GQDs were drop-casted on the surface of PAMAM dendrimers. Another team prepared Si-CDs/Si-dendrimer composites for solar cell applications. The silicone CDs were prepared using citric acid, dicyandiamide, and APTES by the solvothermal method. Then, the Si-CDs were dispersed in the silicone dendrimers (on a glass substrate), forming a uniform film at room temperature and curing for 48 h (Fig. 6
                        ). These silicone CDs/dendrimer composite nanofilms worked properly as luminescent solar cell concentrators [65].
